tories, But I Live includes historical essays, an illustrated postscript from the artists, and personal words from each of the survivors. As we urgently approach the post-witness era without living survivors of the Holocaust, these illustrated stories act as a physical embodiment of memory and help to create a new archive for future readers. By turning these testimonies into graphic novels, But I Live aims to teach new generations about racism, antisemitism, human rights, and social justice.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 4aDISCOUNT-C. 7aHISTORY / Jewish.2bisacsh  aPTSD.  adifficult histories.  agenocide studies.  agraphic novels.  ahigh school classroom.  aholocaust survivors.  ahuman rights.  asocial justice.  atestimonies.  atrauma-informed teaching and learning.  avisual storytelling.1 aArbel, Emmie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDubbelman, Jan Erik, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEisenstein, Bernice, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHondius, Dienke, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHuculak, Matt, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKamp, Nico, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKamp, Rolf, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKorb, Alexander, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLibicki, Miriam, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLöw, Andrea, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchaffer, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchallié, Charlotte, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchallié, 